The plot is showing the number of article **headlines** per every 2 hours containing the words *corona*, *war*, *storm*, *olympia* or *gasoline prices*, collected from the german online papers/magazines/news-channels 
[bild.de](https://www.bild.de), 
[compact-online.de](https://www.compact-online.de/), 
[faz.net](https://www.faz.net/),
[fr.de](https://www.fr.de/),
[gmx.net](https://www.gmx.net/),
[heise.de](https://www.heise.de/),
[spiegel.de](https://www.spiegel.de/),
[spiegeldaily.de](https://www.spiegeldaily.de/),
[sueddeutsche.de](https://www.sueddeutsche.de/),
[t-online.de](https://www.t-online.de/),
[volksstimme.de](https://www.volksstimme.de/),
[web.de](https://web.de),
[welt.de](https://www.welt.de),
[zeit.de](https://www.zeit.de/) and
[zeitfuerdieschule.de](https://www.zeitfuerdieschule.de). Scraping was done by [this repository](https://github.com/defgsus/frontpage-archive-2) and every index page as well as several sub-categories are analyzed. This plot only considers the **first 10 headlines** found on each page.

The [olympic wintergames](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_Winter_Olympics) were helt between 4th and 20th February, 
there was a [heavy storm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Storm_Eunice) around 15th February and the [invasion of Ukraine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine) began the 24th. The evergreen topic of facts and stories about the [pandemic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic) got largly diminished in popularity by the latter event.

Counting the number of pages (categories) containing headlines with the above terms leads to a similar graphic:

For the regarded period, *corona* highly correlates with the *olympic games*, the word *february* and *mandatory vaccination*. whereas on the contrary side *war* highly correlates with *ukraine*, *russia*, *putin*, *refugees*, *invasion* and *gas*. The red areas show negative correlations, which translates to words that suppress or, at least, replace each other in usage.
